# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: csv-tsv
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Early character encodings that originated with optical or electrical telegraphy and in early computers could only represent a subset of the characters used in languages, sometimes restricted to upper case letters, numerals and limited punctuation.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Over time, encodings capable of representing more characters were created, such as ASCII, ISO/IEC 8859, and Unicode encodings such as UTF-8 and UTF-16.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The most popular character encoding on the World Wide Web is UTF-8, which is used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In application programs and operating system tasks, both UTF-8 and UTF-16 are popular options.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The history of character codes illustrates the evolving need for machine-mediated character-based symbolic information over a distance, using once-novel electrical means.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The earliest codes were based upon manual and hand-written encoding and cyphering systems, such as Bacon's cipher, Braille, international maritime signal flags, and the 4-digit encoding of Chinese characters for a Chinese telegraph code (Hans Schjellerup, 1869).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] With the adoption of electrical and electro-mechanical techniques these earliest codes were adapted to the new capabilities and limitations of the early machines.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The earliest well-known electrically transmitted character code, Morse code, introduced in the 1840s, used a system of four "symbols" (short signal, long signal, short space, long space) to generate codes of variable length.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Though some commercial use of Morse code was via machinery, it was often used as a manual code, generated by hand on a telegraph key and decipherable by ear, and persists in amateur radio and aeronautical use.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Most codes are of fixed per-character length or variable-length sequences of fixed-length codes (e.g.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Common examples of character encoding systems include Morse code, the Baudot code, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) and Unicode.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Unicode, a well-defined and extensible encoding system, has replaced most earlier character encodings, but the path of code development to the present is fairly well known.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The Baudot code, a five-bit encoding, was created by Émile Baudot in 1870, patented in 1874, modified by Donald Murray in 1901, and standardized by CCITT as International Telegraph Alphabet No.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The name *baudot* has been erroneously applied to ITA2 and its many variants.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] ITA2 suffered from many shortcomings and was often improved by many equipment manufacturers, sometimes creating compatibility issues.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Herman Hollerith invented punch card data encoding in the late 19th century to analyze census data.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Initially, each hole position represented a different data element, but later, numeric information was encoded by numbering the lower rows 0 to 9, with a punch in a column representing its row number.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Later alphabetic data was encoded by allowing more than one punch per column.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Electromechanical tabulating machines represented date internally by the timing of pulses relative to the motion of the cards through the machine.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] When IBM went to electronic processing, starting with the IBM 603 Electronic Multiplier, it used a variety of binary encoding schemes that were tied to the punch card code.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] IBM used several binary-coded decimal (BCD) six-bit character encoding schemes, starting as early as 1953 in its 702 and 704 computers, and in its later 7000 Series and 1400 series, as well as in associated peripherals.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Since the punched card code then in use was limited to digits, upper-case English letters and a few special characters, six bits were sufficient.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] These BCD encodings extended existing simple four-bit numeric encoding to include alphabetic and special characters, mapping them easily to punch-card encoding which was already in widespread use.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] IBM's codes were used primarily with IBM equipment.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Other computer vendors of the era had their own character codes, often six-bit, such as the encoding used by the UNIVAC I.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] They usually had the ability to read tapes produced on IBM equipment.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] IBM's BCD encodings were the precursors of their Extended Binary-Coded Decimal Interchange Code (usually abbreviated as EBCDIC), an eight-bit encoding scheme developed in 1963 for the IBM System/360 that featured a larger character set, including lower case letters.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In 1959, the U.S. military defined its Fieldata code, a six-or seven-bit code, introduced by the U.S.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] While Fieldata addressed many of the then-modern issues (e.g. letter and digit codes arranged for machine collation), it fell short of its goals and was short-lived.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In 1963 the first ASCII code was released (X3.4-1963) by the ASCII committee (which contained at least one member of the Fieldata committee, W.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Leubbert), which addressed most of the shortcomings of Fieldata, using a simpler seven-bit code.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Many of the changes were subtle, such as collatable character sets within certain numeric ranges.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] ASCII63 was a success, widely adopted by industry, and with the follow-up issue of the 1967 ASCII code (which added lower-case letters and fixed some "control code" issues) ASCII67 was adopted fairly widely.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] ASCII67's American-centric nature was somewhat addressed in the European ECMA-6 standard.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Eight-bit extended ASCII encodings, such as various vendor extensions and the ISO/IEC 8859 series, supported all ASCII characters as well as additional non-ASCII characters.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In 1985, the average personal computer user's hard disk drive could store only about 10 megabytes, and it cost approximately US$250 on the wholesale market (and much higher if purchased separately at retail), so it was very important at the time to make every bit count.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The compromise solution that was eventually found and developed into Unicode was to break the assumption (dating back to telegraph codes) that each character should always directly correspond to a particular sequence of bits.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Instead, characters would first be mapped to a universal intermediate representation in the form of abstract numbers called code points.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Code points would then be represented in a variety of ways and with various default numbers of bits per character (code units) depending on context.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] To encode code points higher than the length of the code unit, such as above 256 for eight-bit units, the solution was to implement variable-length encodings where an escape sequence would signal that subsequent bits should be parsed as a higher code point.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The various terms related to character encoding are often used inconsistently or incorrectly.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Historically, the same standard would specify a repertoire of characters and how they were to be encoded into a stream of code units – usually with a single character per code unit.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] However, due to the emergence of more sophisticated character encodings, the distinction between terms has become important.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A character is the smallest unit of text that has semantic value.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In linguistics, this is called a grapheme and each of the various ways it may be written are called glyphs.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] What constitutes a character varies between character encodings.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] For example, for letters with diacritics, there are two distinct approaches that can be taken to encode them.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] They can be encoded either as a single unified character (known as a precomposed character), or as separate characters that combine into a single glyph.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The former simplifies the text handling system, but the latter allows any letter/diacritic combination to be used in text.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Some writing systems, such as Arabic and Hebrew, have graphemes whose shape and joining depend on context.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A character set is a collection of characters used to represent text.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] For example, the Latin alphabet and Greek alphabet are character sets.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A coded character set is a character set with each item uniquely mapped to a numberic value.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] This is also known as a code page, although that term is generally antiquated.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Originally, *code page* referred to a page number in an IBM manual that defined a particular character encoding.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Other vendors, including Microsoft, SAP, and Oracle Corporation, also published their own code pages, including notable Windows code page and code page 437.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Despite no longer referring to specific pages in a manual, many character encodings are still identified to by the same number.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Likewise, the term *code page* is still used to refer to character encoding.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In Unix and Unix-like systems, the term *charmap* is commonly used; usually in the larger context of locales.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] IBM's Character Data Representation Architecture (CDRA) designates each entity with a coded character set identifier (CCSID), which is variously called a *charset*, *character set*, *code page*, or *CHARMAP*.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A character repertoire is a set of characters that can be represented by a particular coded character set.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The repertoire may be closed, meaning that no additions are allowed without creating a new standard (as is the case with ASCII and most of the ISO-8859 series); or it may be open, allowing additions (as is the case with Unicode and to a limited extent Windows code pages).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A code point is the value or position of a character in a coded character set.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A code point is represented by a sequence of code units.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Code space is the range of numerical values spanned by a coded character set.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A code unit is the minimum bit combination that can represent a character in a character encoding (in computer science terms, it is the word size of the character encoding).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Common code units include 7-bit, 8-bit, 16-bit, and 32-bit.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] In some encodings, some characters are encoded as multiple code units.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Unicode and its parallel standard, the ISO/IEC 10646 Universal Character Set, together constitute a unified standard for character encoding.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The purpose of this decomposition is to establish a universal set of characters that can be encoded in a variety of ways.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] To describe the model precisely, Unicode uses existing terms and defines new terms.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] An abstract character repertoire (ACR) is the full set of abstract characters that a system supports.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Unicode has an open repertoire, meaning that new characters will be added to the repertoire over time.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A coded character set (CCS) is a function that maps characters to *code points* (each code point represents one character).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] For example, in a given repertoire, the capital letter "A" in the Latin alphabet might be represented by the code point 65, the character "B" by 66, and so on.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Multiple coded character sets may share the same character repertoire; for example ISO/IEC 8859-1 and IBM code pages 037 and 500 all cover the same repertoire but map them to different code points.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Hardware and software systems typically have a maximum "native" word length, such as 16 or 32 bits.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A character encoding may define code points whose length exceeds a system's native word length.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] *A character encoding form* (CEF) is the mapping of code points to *code units* that break up a code point in a standardized way so that each code unit fits within the system's word length.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] For example, a computer that represents numbers in 16-bit units can only represent code points up to 65,535 per unit, but larger code points can be represented using multiple 16-bit units as defined by the CEF.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A character encoding scheme (CES) is the mapping of code units to a sequence of octets to facilitate storage on an octet-based file system or transmission over an octet-based network.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] See comparison of Unicode encodings for a detailed discussion.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] There may be a higher-level protocol which supplies additional information to select the particular variant of a Unicode character, particularly where there are regional variants that have been 'unified' in Unicode as the same character.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] An example is the XML attribute xml:lang.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The Unicode model uses the term "character map" for other systems which directly assign a sequence of characters to a sequence of bytes, covering all of the CCS, CEF and CES layers.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] A character is commonly documented as 'U+' followed by its code point value in hexadecimal.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The range of valid code points (the code space) for the Unicode standard is U+0000 to U+10FFFF, inclusive, divided in 17 planes, identified by the numbers 0 to 16.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+0000 to U+FFFF are in plane 0, called the Basic Multilingual Plane (BMP).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] This plane contains the most commonly used characters.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Characters in the range U+10000 to U+10FFFF in the other planes are called supplementary characters.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Consider, "ab̲c𐐀" – a string containing a Unicode combining character (U+0332 ◌̲ COMBINING LOW LINE to underline the ⟨b⟩) as well as a supplementary character (U+10400 𐐀 DESERET CAPITAL LETTER LONG I).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Note in particular that 𐐀 is represented with either one 32-bit value (UTF-32), two 16-bit values (UTF-16), or four 8-bit values (UTF-8).
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] Although each of those forms uses the same total number of bits (32) to represent the grapheme, it is not obvious how the actual numeric byte values are related.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] To support environments using multiple character encodings, software has been developed to translate text between character encoding schemes, a process known as transcoding.
[src:csv-tsv/character-encoding] The most used character encoding on the web is UTF-8, used in 98.9% of surveyed web sites, as of January 2026.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] CSV is not limited to a particular character encoding but should be and is commonly used with UTF-8, particularly because it does not provide a way to indicate the character encoding.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The CSV format predates personal computers by more than a decade.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The IBM Fortran (level H extended) compiler under OS/360 supported list-directed ("free-form") input/output, with commas between values, in 1972.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] List-directed input/output was defined in FORTRAN 77, approved in 1978.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] List-directed input used commas or spaces for delimiters, so unquoted character strings could not contain commas or spaces.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The term "comma-separated value" and the "CSV" abbreviation were in use by 1983.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The manual for the Osborne Executive computer, which bundled the SuperCalc spreadsheet, documents the CSV quoting convention that allows strings to contain embedded commas.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Comma-separated value lists are easier to type (for example into punched cards) than fixed-column-aligned data, and they were less prone to producing incorrect results if a value was punched one column off from its intended location.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Comma separated files are used for the interchange of database information between machines of two different architectures.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The plain-text character of CSV files largely avoids incompatibilities such as byte-order and word size.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The files are largely human-readable, so it is easier to deal with them in the absence of perfect documentation or communication.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The main standardization initiative—transforming "*de facto* fuzzy definition" into a more precise and *de jure* one—was in 2005, with RFC 4180, defining CSV as a MIME Content Type.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Later, in 2013, some of RFC 4180's deficiencies were tackled by a W3C recommendation.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] In 2014 IETF published RFC 7111 describing the application of URI fragments to CSV documents.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] RFC 7111 specifies how row, column, and cell ranges can be selected from a CSV document using position indexes.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] In 2015 W3C, in an attempt to enhance CSV with formal semantics, publicized the first *drafts of recommendations* for CSV metadata standards, which began as *recommendations* in December of the same year.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] CSV can be informally described as plain text data consisting of one record per line, where each line has the same sequence of fields separated by a comma.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The format is more formally described in the 2005 technical standard RFC 4180 which codifies the CSV format and defines the MIME type `text/csv` for the handling of text-based fields.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] This example illustrates that a CSV cannot be parsed by naïvely splitting the data by line terminators into lines, and then each line by commas.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] In 2011, Open Knowledge Foundation (OKF) and various partners created a data protocols working group, which later evolved into the Frictionless Data initiative.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] One of the main formats they released was the Tabular Data Package.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Tabular Data package was heavily based on CSV, using it as the main data transport format and adding basic type and schema metadata.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] (CSV lacks any type information to distinguish the string `1` from the number 1.) The Frictionless Data Initiative has also provided a standard CSV Dialect Description Format for describing different dialects of CSV, for example specifying the field separator or quoting rules.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] In 2013, the W3C "CSV on the Web" working group began to specify technologies providing higher interoperability for web applications using CSV or similar formats.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] The working group completed its work in February 2016 and is officially closed in March 2016 with the release of a set of documents and W3C recommendations for modeling "Tabular Data", and enhancing CSV with metadata and semantics.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] While the well-formedness of CSV data can readily be checked, testing validity and canonical form is less well developed, relative to more precise data formats, such as XML and SQL, which offer richer types and rules-based validation.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] CSV is commonly used for data exchange and is widely supported by data-oriented applications.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] It is often used to move tabular data between programs that natively operate on incompatible data – often in formats that are proprietary or undocumented.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] A common scenario is moving data from a database to a spreadsheet which, in general, use completely different formats.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Most database systems can export as CSV and most spreadsheet programs can import CSV-formatted data, leveraging CSV as an intermediate format.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Every major ecommerce platform provides support for exporting data as a CSV file.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Common data science tools such as Pandas include the option to export data to CSV for long-term storage.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Benefits of CSV for data storage include the simplicity of CSV makes parsing and creating CSV files easy to implement and fast compared to other data formats, human readability making editing or fixing data simpler, and high compressibility leading to smaller data files.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Alternatively, CSV does not support more complex data relations and makes no distinction between null and empty values, and in applications where these features are needed other formats are preferred.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] More than 200 local, regional, and national data portals, such as those of the UK government and the European Commission, use CSV files with standardized data catalogs.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Some applications use CSV as a data interchange format to enhance its interoperability, exporting and importing CSV.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] CSV is supported by almost all spreadsheets and database management systems.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Spreadsheets including Apple Numbers, LibreOffice Calc, and Apache OpenOffice Calc. support reading CSV files.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Microsoft Excel also supports a dialect of CSV with restrictions in comparison to other spreadsheet software (e.g., as of 2019 Excel still cannot export CSV files in the commonly used UTF-8 character encoding, and separator is not enforced to be the comma).
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] LibreOffice Calc CSV importer is actually a more generic delimited text importer, supporting multiple separators at the same time as well as field trimming.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Various relational databases support saving query results to a CSV file.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] PostgreSQL provides the `COPY` command, which allows for both saving and loading data to and from a file.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] `COPY (SELECT * FROM articles) TO '/home/wikipedia/file.csv' (FORMAT csv)` saves the content of a table `articles` to a file called `/home/wikipedia/file.csv`.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Some relational databases, when using standard SQL, offer *foreign-data wrapper* (FDW).
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] For example, PostgreSQL offers the `CREATE FOREIGN TABLE` and `CREATE EXTENSION file_fdw` commands to configure any variant of CSV.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Databases like Apache Hive offer the option to express CSV or .csv.gz as an internal table format.
[src:csv-tsv/comma-separated-values] Programs that work with CSV may have limits on the maximum number of rows CSV files can have.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] Data exchange is similar to data integration except that data may be restructured with possible loss of content.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] There may be no way to transform a particular collection based on exchange constraints.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] Conversely, there may be multiple ways to transform the data, in which case one option must be identified in order to achieve compatibility between source and target.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] There are two main types of data exchange: broadcast and peer-to-peer (a.k.a. unicast).
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] For broadcast, data is transmitted simultaneously to all consumers.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] Just as a conference call, all participants get the same information from the speaker at the same time.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] For peer-to-peer, data is sent to a single receiver, defined by a specific address.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] For example, a letter goes to just one mail box.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] In some domains, a multiple source and target schema (proprietary data formats) may exist.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] An exchange or interchange format is often developed for a single domain, and then necessary routines (mappings) are written to (indirectly) transform/translate each and every source schema to each and every target schema by using the interchange format as an intermediate step.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] That requires less work than writing and debugging the many routines that would be required to directly translate each source schema directly to each target schema.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] A data exchange (a.k.a. interchange) language defines a domain-independent way to represent data.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] These languages have evolved from being markup and display-oriented to support the encoding of metadata that describes the structural attributes of the information.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] Practice has shown that certain types of formal languages are better suited for this task than others, since their specification is driven by a formal process instead of particular software implementation.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] For example, XML is a markup language that was designed to enable the creation of dialects (the definition of domain-specific sublanguages).
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] However, it does not contain domain-specific dictionaries or fact types.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] Beneficial to a reliable data exchange is the availability of standard dictionaries-taxonomies and tools libraries such as parsers, schema validators, and transformation tools.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] The popularity of XML for data exchange on the World Wide Web has several reasons.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] First of all, it is closely related to the preexisting standards Standard Generalized Markup Language (SGML) and Hypertext Markup Language (HTML), and as such a parser written to support these two languages can be easily extended to support XML as well.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] For example, XHTML has been defined as a format that is formal XML, but understood correctly by most (if not all) HTML parsers.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] YAML was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor with notion similar to reStructuredText and wiki syntax.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] YAML 1.2 also includes a shorthand notion that is compatible with JSON, and as such any JSON document is also valid YAML; this however does not hold the other way.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] REBOL was designed to be human-readable and authored via a text editor.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] It uses a simple free-form syntax with minimal punctuation and a rich set of data types (such as URL, email, date and time, tuple, string, tag) that respect common standards.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] It is designed to not need any additional meta-language, being designed in a metacircular fashion which is why the parse dialect used for definitions and transformations of REBOL dialects is also itself a dialect of REBOL.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] REBOL was used as a source of inspiration for JSON.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] The dictionary also includes standardized fact types.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] The terms and relation types together can be used to create and interpret expressions of facts, knowledge, requirements and other information.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] Gellish can be used in combination with SQL, RDF/XML, OWL and various other meta-languages.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] The Gellish standard is a combination of ISO 10303-221 (AP221) and ISO 15926.
[src:csv-tsv/data-exchange] The following describes and compares popular data exchange languages.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] A **delimited text file** is a text file that stores data as DSV.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Such a file can be classified as a flat-file database if, in fact, the data is database-like – accessing individual rows is meaningful.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] A commonly used alternative for text data is fixed-width where each column has the same number of characters – limiting the length of each field value.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] In contrast, DSV supports field values of any length.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] DSV is a categorization of data format, not a particular format.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] To be useful, a convention must be established that defines the precise format.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] In general a format is categorized as DSV if it is lines of delimiter-separated values (where lines are newline-separated).
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] The first row is sometimes a special record containing the column names.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Any character may be used to separate field values, and the more commonly used include comma, tab, colon, vertical bar (a.k.a. pipe) and space.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] ASCII and Unicode include control characters that are intended to be used as delimiters: File Separator, Group Separator, Record Separator, and Unit Separator.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Use of these in DSV data is relatively uncommon although the MARC 21 bibliographic data format does.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Two commonly-used sub-categories of DSV, comma-separated values (CSV) and tab-separated values (TSV), are supported by many software packages including many spreadsheet and statistical applications.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Some can import such data even without the user describing the format – such as which character to use as the delimiter.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Even though such an application may more directly support a more capable and possibly proprietary internal data model (for example, accdb or xlsx), they can map DSV data to their internal data model.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] A particular challenge of DSV is delimiter collision – what happens when the delimiter character is embedded in a field value without accommodation for doing so.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] The character is interpreted as a separator – splitting a single, logical value into two.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Some DSV conventions simply disallow a delimiter in a value while others provide a mechanism that allows for embedding delimiters.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] A commonly-used way to avoid delimiter collision is to enclose a field value in double quotes.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] A convention could require this for all values or it could be optional so that it might only be used for values that have an embedded delimiter.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Collision can be avoided if the convention disallows the delimiter in a field value; the tacit implication if the convention provides no way to avoid collision.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Using a relatively unusual character (e.g. tilde `~`) limits the impact on possible field values.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] But, even though a character may seem unusual, in practice, it might be used and then result in a processing error.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] In the following example, the table is formatted per typical CSV: fields separated by a comma.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Each field value is enclosed in double quotes so that a field value can contain a comma.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] The comma in `"Bloggs, Fred"` is not a value separator because the text is enclosed in double-quotes.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] Some formats allow newline to be included in a value via this mechanism.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] To encode a double quote in a value, two double quotes are used where the first one acts as an escape character so that the second one is interpreted as a double quote instead of field begin or end.
[src:csv-tsv/delimiter-separated-values] The value `"Muniz, Alvin ""Hank"""` is interpreted as `Muniz, Alvin "Hank"`.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] A **flat-file database** is a tabular flat file in which each record is semantically independent – can meaningfully be interpreted and manipulated independent of other records of the table.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The term *flat* loosely refers to data that is record-based and sequential yet lacks more complicated aspects such as nesting, relationships and metadata (with the exception of column headers).
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Relationships can be inferred from the data, but the format does not provide special accommodations for relationships.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] A flat-file database may be stored as plain text or binary (not character encoded).
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] When plain text, it is typically formatted as one record per line either as delimiter-separated or fixed-width.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] In delimiter-separated values files, the fields are separated by a character or string called the delimiter.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Common variants are comma-separated values (CSV) where the delimiter is a comma, tab-separated values (TSV) where the delimiter is the tab character, space-separated values and vertical-bar-separated values (delimiter is `|`).
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] If the delimiter is allowed inside a field, there needs to be a way to distinguish delimiters characters or strings that are meant literally.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] For example, consider the sentence "If I have to, I'll do it myself.".
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] To encode it in CSV, there needs to be a way to prevent the comma from splitting the field.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Several strategies to prevent delimiter collision exist.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] With fixed-width formats, each field has a fixed length with extra spaces added as needed.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The fixed lengths can be predefined and known ahead of time (i.e. stated in the format's specification), or parsed from a header.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] With predefined lengths, fields are limited to a maximum length.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The need for longer fields may appear sometime after the format is defined.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Possible workarounds include abbreviating phrases, replacing values with links (e.g. a URI pointing to the value), and splitting a file into multiple files.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] With delimiter-separated formats, determining the field boundaries requires finding the delimiters, which incurs some computational overhead.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] This is not needed for fixed-width formats.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] However, fixed-width formats can lead to unnecessarily large file sizes if fields tend to be shorter than the lengths reserved for them.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Delimiters can be used alongside a notation stating the length of each field.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] For example, `5apple|9pineapple` specifies the length (5 and 9) of each field.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] It has low overhead and trivially avoids delimiter collisions, but it is brittle when edited manually.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] In the 1980s, configurable flat-file database computer applications were popular on the IBM PC and the Macintosh.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] These programs were designed to make it easy for individuals to design and use their own databases, and were almost on par with word processors and spreadsheets in popularity.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Examples of flat-file database software include early versions of FileMaker and the shareware PC-File and the popular dBase.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Flat-file databases are common and ubiquitous because they are easy to write and edit, and suit myriad purposes in an uncomplicated way.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Linear stores of NoSQL data, JSON data, primitive spreadsheets (perhaps comma-separated or tab-delimited), and text files can all be seen as flat-file databases because they lack integrated indexes, built-in references between data elements, and complex data types.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Programs to manage collections of books or appointments and address books may use single-purpose flat-file databases, storing and retrieving information from flat-files unadorned with indexes or pointing systems.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] While a user can write a table of contents into a text file, the text file format itself does not include a concept of a table of contents.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] While a user may write "friends with Kathy" in the "Notes" section for John's contact information, this is interpreted by the user rather than a built-in feature of the database.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] In the context of Unix-like systems, the files `/etc/passwd` and `/etc/group` are flat-files databases.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The following illustrates typical elements of a flat-file database.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The information is arranged as a table – a series of rows and columns.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The first row specifies the field names that are associated with the values of each row.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] The columns consist of an identifier (*id*), a person's name (*name*) and a team name (*team*).
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Columns are separated by whitespace characters.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] This is also called indentation or "fixed-width" data formatting.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Another common convention is to separate columns using one or more delimiter characters, such as a tab or comma.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Each column may be restricted to a specific data type with restrictions usually enforced by convention.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Each row or record meets the standard definition of a tuple under relational algebra.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] This example depicts a series of 3-tuples.
[src:csv-tsv/flat-file-database] Since the formal operations possible with a text file are usually more limited than desired, the text in the above example would ordinarily represent an intermediary state of the data prior to being transferred into a database management system.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] TSV is a relatively simple format and is widely supported for data exchange by software that generally deals with tabular data.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] For example, a TSV file might be used to transfer information from a database to a spreadsheet.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] The following are records of the Iris flower data set in TSV format.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Since a tab is not a printable character (is invisible), an arrow (→) is used for demonstration here to denote a tab character.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] The following is the same data rendered as a table.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] If a text editor that supports Dynamic tab stops (aka.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] "elastic tabstops") is used to view the contents of a TSV file, the layout will look like the table rendering just without cell borders and header row formatting (though the latter can be achieved using Unicode characters).
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Non-technical users, who are editing TSV with a text editor, sometimes mix up tabs and spaces, corrupting the data.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Empty fields may also be difficult to count in editors where tabs are merely shown as whitespace.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Despite lower complexity, fewer applications implement it.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] The file size increase of quoting both commas and quotes in CSV is usually insignificant on modern systems.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Terminal emulators often render tabs as multiple spaces which prevents copying a tab correctly, thus preventing copying TSV formatted data directly from a selection on the terminal without combining all fields into one.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] As a form of delimiter collision, if a field (record value) contained a tab character, the data format would become meaningless since tabs were no longer *only* used between fields.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] To prevent this situation, the IANA media type standard for TSV simply disallows a tab within a field.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Similarly, a value cannot contain a line terminator.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] To represent a value with an embedded tab or line terminator character, a commonly-used mechanism is to replace the character with the corresponding escape sequence as shown in the following table.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Another commonly-used convention, borrowed from CSV (RFC 4180), is to enclose a value that contains a tab or line terminator character in quotes.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Among others it's used by LibreOffice Calc where the backslash (\) notation is not implemented and TSV is simply treated as a variant of CSV with tab delimiters instead of comma.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] As for any text file, the character(s) used for line terminator varies.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] On a Microsoft-based system, normally it's a carriage return (CR) and line feed (LF) sequence.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] The de-facto specification uses the term "EOL" which is an ambiguous term like line terminator and newline.
[src:csv-tsv/tab-separated-values] Software often is designed to either handle the line terminator for the platform on which it runs or to handle either terminator.
